resources.string: 2D Barcode which can encode all the 256 ASCII and extended ASCII characters (3832 digits, 3067 letters, or 1914 bytes of data)

Codabar (sometimes called Code 2 of 7) is a discrete, width–modulated barcode that provides a character set for encoding numeric data (0–9) plus six special characters ($, -, :, /, ., +) (43 characters including numbers)
The Data Matrix is high-density, two-dimensional (2D) barcode that encodes text, numbers, files and actual data bytes (5067 digits, 3804 letters, or 2532 binary data)
Maxicode (barcode) uses dots in hexagonal grid for representing information (93 characters of information)
The Code 39 specification defines 43 characters, consisting of uppercase letters (A through Z), numeric digits (0 through 9) and a number of special characters (-, ., $, /, +, %, and space)
Code 93 was designed to complement and improve upon Code 39 (up to 47 characters)
Code 128 was designed to complement and improve upon Code 128 (Supports Unicode, up to 60 characters)
It\'s usually use to identify a specific retail product details (8 characters)
It\'s usually use to identify a specific retail product details (13 characters)
ITF is the GS1 implementation of an ITf bar code to encode a Global Trade Item Number (up to 14 Characters)
PDF417 is a stacked linear barcode symbol format used in a variety of applications, primarily transport, identification cards, and inventory management (up to 850 characters)
Qr code are typically used for storing URLs or other information for reading by the camera on a smartphone(2157 digits, 1307 letters, or 898 bytes of data)

DataBar barcode are often used to label fresh foods. These barcode can hold information like an item\'s batch number or expiry date, in addition to other attributes used at the point-of-sale such the item weight (14 Numeric Characters)
Expanded Version of RSS-14 (41 Alphanumeric or 74 Numeric)

UPC-A, UPC-E, and EAN-13 can all have an additional barcode located to the right of the main barcode that contains additional information. This second barcode is normally not as tall as the primary barcode and can encode either two or five additional digits. Supplement 2 encodes two digits

The Universal Product Code (UPC) is a barcode symbology that is widely used in the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand, in Europe and other countries for tracking trade items in stores (12 Numeric Characters)
